# Spec-driven development

[`ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md`](../../ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md) is the contract for "done". Every non-trivial change binds to at least one `AC-xx` ID there.

## Before you code

- **Identify the ACs.** List the `AC-xx` IDs the change satisfies, modifies, or would newly introduce. Skim §12 Non-Goals to confirm the task is in scope.
- **If no AC covers it**, propose an AC amendment first (see [`ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md`](../../ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md) §Amending ACs). Do not code silently against an unwritten spec.
- **If the task conflicts with §12 Non-Goals**, stop and ask — non-goals can only be relaxed with explicit human approval per [`change-boundary.mdc`](change-boundary.mdc).

## Ambiguity protocol

If an AC is silent, self-contradictory, or disagrees with Figma:

1. Do **not** pick arbitrarily.
2. Either (a) propose a one-paragraph AC patch (add / edit / deprecate per §Amending ACs), or (b) ask the user for the intended behaviour.
3. For visual conflicts, Figma wins — follow [`project.mdc`](project.mdc) §Figma-first workflow and update the AC + token, not the design.

When amending or adding an AC, follow [`ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md` §10.6 AC Authoring](../../ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md#106-ac-authoring) — specificity tracks the stability marker, and node IDs / tokens / fixed counts live in their single source (§2.5 Figma Manifest, [`src/styles/variables.css`](../../src/styles/variables.css), §12.1 Product Decisions), not restated in AC bodies.

## Traceability

- Commit messages and PR descriptions list every `AC-xx` touched (e.g. `AC-20d, AC-31`).
- If a new component or behaviour does not map to an existing AC, the same PR must add the new AC and, when visual, the matching row in §2.5 Figma Manifest.
- When you add or amend an AC body in the same PR, annotate the AC with the inline log marker defined in [`ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md` §10.5 Amendment logging](../../ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md#105-amending-acs) — `(added YYYY-MM, #PR)` for new ACs, `(amended YYYY-MM, #PR)` for edits. Deprecations use the tombstone line instead; the convention is not retroactive on pre-GOV-10 ACs.
- AC-IDs are **immutable** — never renumber, never reuse a retired ID. When an AC's meaning changes materially, tombstone the old ID and mint a new one per §10.5 Tombstone format.
- Tests, when added, reference the AC-ID in the test name / description (e.g. `AC-15: empty submit is a no-op`).

## Self-review before finishing

For non-trivial changes, end the turn with a short AC checklist:

- For each touched `AC-xx`, state how it was verified — build / lint / test signal from [`verification.mdc`](verification.mdc), manual dev-harness steps from [`ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md`](../../ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md) §11 Definition of Done, or Figma node checked per [`project.mdc`](project.mdc).
- If an AC in scope could not be verified this turn, say so explicitly rather than implying coverage.
- For larger changes, consider running [`scripts/prompts/ac-review.md`](../../scripts/prompts/ac-review.md) in a separate turn for an adversarial second pass.

## Deference

This rule only governs the spec↔code binding. It does **not** restate:

- Build / lint / smoke commands — see [`verification.mdc`](verification.mdc).
- Approval gates for deps, `vite.config.ts`, public API, CI — see [`change-boundary.mdc`](change-boundary.mdc).
- Stack conventions, typing, input handlers — see [`code-governance.mdc`](code-governance.mdc).
- Figma-first visual workflow and node manifest — see [`project.mdc`](project.mdc) and §2.5 of `ACCEPTANCE_CRITERIA.md`.
- Host-page safety for the embedded bundle — see [`embed-safety.mdc`](embed-safety.mdc).
